<TITLE> Thai court to hear case against Thaksin ally </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BANGKOK, March 20 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Thailand's Supreme Court agreed on Thursday to hear a case against a senior member of the ruling People Power Party (PPP) accused of buying votes in a December poll, which could lead to the party's dissolution. A three-judge panel agreed to consider the case against PPP deputy leader Yongyut Tiyapairat, who stepped down as speaker of parliament after the Election Commission (EC) sent its findings to the court in February. The EC accused Yongyut, a key ally of former Prime Minister Thaksin Shinawatra ousted in a bloodless 2006 coup, of mobilising village chiefs to buy votes in the poll that elected a PPP-led, pro-Thaksin coalition government. The Supreme Court could take up to three months to rule on the case, a senior court official said. If it found Yongyut guilty, the EC could then investigate whether the party itself was involved and pass its findings to the Constitutional Court, which could take at least a year to deliver its ruling, analysts sa
